Frequency Bands
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most important differentiation criteria for RFID systems are the operating
 frequency of the reader.
 Selecting the most adequate frequency is a function of the following properties
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Technical properties of the application e.g.
 The RFID channel contains metals or not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cost of the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Behavior of the electromagnetic waves at these different frequencies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First RFID systems started with Low Frequency (LF) 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "LF"
description "Low Frequency"

\end_inset

 band RFID systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LF_RFID"

\end_inset

.
 After few years, the RFID systems have operated in High Frequency (HF)
 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "HF"
description "High Frequency"

\end_inset

 band 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HF_RFID"

\end_inset

.
 Using only these two band made a big limitation on the RFID applications.
 Thus, Recent years, the number of RFID systems operating in the Ultra High
 Frequency (UHF) 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "UHF"
description "Ultra High Frequency"

\end_inset

 range have increased because of the dramatic decrease in its component's
 price 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "UHF_RFID"

\end_inset

.
 Thus, it is expected to see the RFID microwave band more available and
 affordable in the market.
 The availability of all bands with affordable costs will give the RFID
 users more facilities to take easier decision in which band they need to
 build up their applications.
\end_layout

