\begin_layout Subsection
Tag Collisions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This type of collision is the most common type of collision in dense RFID
 systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tags_collision_2,Tags_collision_1,Tags_collision_3,Tags_collision_4"

\end_inset

.
 In such systems, we have a single RFID reader and multiple tags as shown
 in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Multiple-tags-to"

\end_inset

.
 The main objective is to identify all tags in the reading area in the minimum
 possible time.
 However, in dense networks, the number of tag collisions increases, which
 decreases the reading efficiency, and hence increases the reading time.
 Different research groups are currently associated with how efficiently
 develop an anti-collision protocol for such systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Anti-collision protocols can be classified into two main types: Physical
 layer protocols and MAC layers protocols.
 
